[h3 id=AboutTheGame 
	"About the game
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"This is an unofficial port of a text adventure game made for CSSCGC 19, a competition for coding crap games held online in 2014. 
	[em 
		"Brad - The Game
	]em
	" was written by Elbe Spurling, formerly known as Brendan Powell Smith,
	[a id=r1 
	]a
	[sup 
		"[
		[a href=#1 
			"1
		]a
		"]
	]sup
	" and is very loosely based on her own family members. In 
	[em 
		"Brad - The Game
	]em
	", you control the author's uncle, a filthy basement dweller whose aspirations are cruising around in his van, scoring with his dream girl Katie and getting another cameo appearance on 
	[em 
		[a href=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Webster_(TV_series) rel=noopener external nofollow 
			"Webster
		]a
	]em
	". You can read a review of the ZX Spectrum port 
	[a href=https://web.archive.org/web/20220808064228/http://mykeweb.co.uk/csscgc2014/review.php?name=eqbtg&site=text rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"on the CSSCGC 19 website
	]a
	" (archived link).
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"This run aims to complete an ending in normal mode. The original game was coded in HTML, while the ZX Spectrum port by Paul E. Collins converts the game to BASIC. It is one of the largest ZX Spectrum files in .tap format, at 1.5 MB. The port uses a multiload system with deliberately inefficient data block arrangement,
	[a id=r2 
	]a
	[sup 
		"[
		[a href=#2 
			"2
		]a
		"]
	]sup
	" which results in excruciating loading times. Loading the start screen without fast load takes around 
	[em 
		"three hours,
	]em
	" and to load the next screen would take 
	[em 
		"even longer.
	]em
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	[em 
		"However
	]em
	", we have the power of BizHawk on our side üòè. Using the Datacorder controls in TAStudio, we can skip to the exact block we need to progress while running the game. Is it hacking, and therefore an invalid run? 
	[em 
		"Yeah
	]em
	", but I ain't got time fo' dat üò§.
	$LF
]div
